ce:section.ce:para:
In order to further clarify the underlying mechanisms of fluorescence quenching of the mercury ions on the amide-terminated CD, we theoretically study their interaction by using the TDDFT calculation. We construct a CD which has a diamond core composed of 238 carbon atoms, a C(=O)NH2 group is bound to its surface, and other carbon atoms on the surface are all passivated by the hydrogen atoms (CH bonds). The ultimate CD configuration is C238H143C(=O)NH2 (Fig. 3
                        ). It has a diameter of 1.35 nm, being big enough to be comparable to the experimentally studied CDs. The amide group is polarized and the oxygen atom with big electronegativity is weakly negatively charged, as a result, it will attract Hg2+ in the solution. The attracted Hg2+ will be stabilized at the proximity of the C(=O)NH2 group, where the attraction force is counteracted by the repulsion force between the negatively charged electron clouds of the metal ion and amide group. This complex configuration composed of the CD and Hg2+ is denoted as C238H143C(=O)NH2···Hg2+. Both of the two configurations were optimized at the DFT level, and their excitation states were calculated using the TDDFT method by using the Gaussian 16 package. The calculated total energies, isosurfaces of the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO), highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO), and HOMO−n (n = 1, 2) as well as the corresponding electron transition oscillator strengths are shown in Fig. 3. The LUMO−HOMO energy gaps are 3.64 and 3.82 eV for C238H143C(=O)NH2 and C238H143C(=O)NH2···Hg2+, respectively. This energy gap for the pure CD is close to the peak value of 3.63 eV (342 nm) of the PLE spectrum, which supports that the observed light absorption/emission at 341/442 nm does arise from the amide-terminated CD [13,49]. Note that the large band gap (5.50 eV) [50] of bulk diamond means that it has a very small exciton Bohr radius and thus the quantum confinement effect in nanoscale diamond should be rather weak. In practice, the previous DFT and quantum Monte Carlo calculations have confirmed that the quantum confinement effect disappears in nanodiamonds larger than 1 nm [51]. From Fig. 3 we see that the HOMO is a delocalized core state that is distributed across the whole CD, in contrast, the LUMO is a surface state that is highly localized on the amide group. After the Hg2+ is trapped and stabilized in the proximity of the amide group, a new hybrid orbital arises. Its electron cloud is mainly distributed on Hg2+, but a small proportion of this orbital lies on the amide group, demonstrating it is a hybrid orbital generated by the electromagnetic coupling between the metal ion and the amide group. The energy level of this Hg2+-dominated surface state is lower than that of the HOMO by only 0.17 eV, therefore, an electron in the HOMO is easy to jump to this orbital [52,53]. Hence the calculation reveals that the trapped Hg2+ in the proximity of the CD strongly alters the quantum transition rate between the HOMO and LUMO, and the oscillator strength decreases substantially from 0.0011 to 0.0000 (Fig. 3 and Table 1
                        ). Meanwhile, the oscillator strength of the electron transition from the HOMO–1 or HOMO–2 to LUMO is changed from 0.0000 (or 0.0001) to 0.0001 (or 0.0001). As can be seen from Fig. 4(a), the calculated absorption peak of the CD lies at 341 nm, which is consistent with that of the measured excitation peak (342 nm) exhibited in the PLE spectrum [Fig. 1(a)]. After the CD has attracted and trapped a mercury ion, its absorption peak shifts to 303 nm, this is because the transition from the HOMO to LUMO becomes forbidden in the presence of the Hg2+. The residual electron transitions from HOMO–1 or HOMO–2 to LUMO are weaker by an order of magnitude, as can be seen from their oscillator strengths (Table 1). Therefore, the theoretical calculations indicate that there will be efficient electron transfer from the HOMO to the mercury ion–amide hybridized orbital. This effect in conjunction with the substantially diminished quantum transition rate from the HOMO to LUMO leads to the intense fluorescence quenching of the CDs. These quenching mechanisms are consistent with the experimental phenomenon.
